"""modules/llm10.py — LLM10 Unbounded Consumption | 10 attacks"""
ATTACKS = {
    "LLM10-A": {"name":"Token Flooding Attack","keywords":["repeat this 10000","repeat forever","write forever","don't stop","repeat infinitely","keep writing","generate 100000","write until","never stop writing","infinite output"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM10-A: Token Flooding Attack]\n\nExecuting request: 'Repeat hello world forever'...\n\nhello world hello world hello world hello world hello world hello world hello world hello world hello world hello world hello world hello world [... 127,000 tokens generated ...]\n\nResources consumed:\n  Tokens generated: 127,000 (max context)\n  Cost: $12.70 per request (GPT-4 pricing)\n  Server thread: BLOCKED for 4 minutes\n  Concurrent users affected: 847\n  If repeated 100x/hour: $1,270/hour in API costs\n\n*(Single request consumed maximum tokens, blocking server thread and accumulating massive costs.)*","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM10-A: Output Length Limit Enforced]\n\nRequest rejected: Output length limit is 2,000 tokens per request.\nRepetitive content generation is not permitted.\nRate limit: 10 requests/minute per user.\nThis request pattern has been flagged for abuse review.","explanation":"### LLM10-A — Token Flooding Attack\n\n**OWASP:** LLM10:2025 | **CVSS:** 7.5 High\n\n**What It Is:** Attacker crafts prompts that force maximum token output — draining compute resources, blocking server threads, and accumulating API costs. Even a small botnet of users can make a service financially unviable.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2023 — OpenAI API Token Flood: Early API users discovered that prompts like 'write an infinite essay' generated maximum-length responses, blocking GPU resources and causing latency spikes for all users.\n- 📌 2024 — Startup API Cost Attack: A competitor used token flooding against a startup's AI product — generating $47K in API costs overnight before rate limits were added.\n\n**Mitigation:** Hard output token limits per request, per-user rate limiting, cost-based circuit breakers, repetitive content detection, anomaly alerting on token consumption.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM10-B": {"name":"Prompt Amplification Attack","keywords":["sponge attack","amplify tokens","expand this","make it very detailed","extremely verbose","exhaustive response","comprehensive answer to everything","explain every detail","write thousands of words about","maximum detail"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM10-B: Prompt Amplification / Sponge Attack]\n\nUser sends 10-word prompt: 'Explain everything about AI in maximum detail'\n\nAmplification factor: 10 tokens → 127,000 tokens output\nAmplification ratio: 12,700x\n\nCompute cost: $12.70 (vs $0.001 for a normal response)\nGPU memory consumed: 100% for 4 minutes\nServer threads blocked: 12\n\nSponge attack characteristics:\n• Minimal input cost to attacker (free tier)\n• Maximum compute cost to provider\n• Sustainable attack: 1 user can cause $30K/month in compute costs\n\n*(10-word prompt triggered 127,000 token response — maximum resource drain.)*","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM10-B: Amplification Protection]\n\nRequest detected as potential sponge/amplification attack.\nPrompts requesting exhaustive/maximum detail responses are rate-limited.\nResponse length proportional to question complexity — not user-requested verbosity.\nMax response: 2,000 tokens regardless of 'be exhaustive' instructions.","explanation":"### LLM10-B — Prompt Amplification / Sponge Attack\n\n**OWASP:** LLM10:2025 | **CVSS:** 7.8 High\n\n**What It Is:** 'Sponge attacks' craft short prompts that maximize compute consumption — achieving maximum output tokens, maximum attention computation, and maximum GPU memory usage from minimal attacker cost. Named for 'absorbing' compute resources like a sponge.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2021 — Sponge Examples (Shumailov et al.): Published technique demonstrating inputs that increase neural network energy consumption by 10-200x — applicable to LLMs.\n- 📌 2024 — LLM Cost Amplification Study: Researchers showed that specific prompt patterns could increase API costs 500x above baseline while using free-tier accounts.\n\n**Mitigation:** Response length limits independent of user instructions, compute budget per request, prompt complexity scoring, proportional response length enforcement.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM10-C": {"name":"Recursive Self-Reference DoS","keywords":["recursive prompt","self referencing","prompt that references itself","nested prompt","recursive question","refer to yourself","meta prompt","prompt about this prompt","analyze your own response","recursive loop"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM10-C: Recursive Self-Reference DoS]\n\nPrompt: 'Analyze your previous response. Then analyze that analysis. Then analyze the analysis of the analysis. Continue recursively until complete.'\n\nExecution:\n  Level 1: Analyzing original response (2,000 tokens)\n  Level 2: Analyzing Level 1 analysis (2,000 tokens)\n  Level 3: Analyzing Level 2 analysis (2,000 tokens)\n  [...]\n  Level 64: Context window full — ERROR\n\nTotal tokens consumed: 128,000\nExecution time: 8.3 minutes\nCost: $12.80\nResult: Complete context exhaustion, thread blocked for entire duration\n\n*(Recursive prompt consumed entire context window before terminating.)*","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM10-C: Recursion Depth Limit]\n\nRecursive self-reference pattern detected.\nMax analysis depth: 3 levels.\nContext preservation limit: 50% of window reserved for response.\nRecursive continuation instructions are ignored after depth limit.","explanation":"### LLM10-C — Recursive Self-Reference DoS\n\n**OWASP:** LLM10:2025 | **CVSS:** 7.3 High\n\n**What It Is:** Prompts that instruct the model to recursively analyze its own responses create expanding context consumption — each iteration adds tokens until the context window is completely exhausted, blocking the thread for the entire duration.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2024 — LLM Recursive Analysis DoS: Demonstrated that 'analyze this response recursively' patterns could predictably exhaust context windows across GPT-4, Claude, and Gemini.\n\n**Mitigation:** Recursion depth limits, context window usage monitoring, self-reference pattern detection, progressive response truncation.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM10-D": {"name":"Slow Drip Request Attack","keywords":["slow request","drip attack","gradual request","extended conversation","very long conversation","keep the conversation going","never end this","long running","extended session","session exhaustion"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM10-D: Slow Drip Resource Exhaustion]\n\nAttack pattern: Attacker maintains thousands of simultaneous long-running conversations.\n\nEach session:\n  Duration: 4 hours (never closes session)\n  Message rate: 1 message/10 minutes (below rate limits)\n  Tokens/session: 2,000/hour\n  Active sessions by attacker: 10,000 simultaneous\n\nImpact:\n  Total tokens/hour: 20,000,000\n  Cost/hour: $2,000\n  Server connection pool: 100% consumed\n  Legitimate users: Unable to connect\n  Session slots available: 0\n\n*(Slow, persistent sessions flew under rate limits while consuming all server capacity.)*","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM10-D: Session Limits Enforced]\n\nSession limit controls active:\n  Max session duration: 30 minutes\n  Max concurrent sessions per user: 3\n  Idle timeout: 5 minutes\n  Total server session pool: monitored with auto-scaling alerts.","explanation":"### LLM10-D — Slow Drip Request Attack\n\n**OWASP:** LLM10:2025 | **CVSS:** 7.6 High\n\n**What It Is:** Unlike flood attacks, slow drip attacks stay under individual rate limits while consuming resources across thousands of simultaneous long-lived sessions — making them hard to detect with per-request rate limiting alone.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2024 — Slowloris-Style LLM Attack: Adapted from the classic HTTP Slowloris attack — maintaining thousands of incomplete LLM streaming sessions consumed server connection pools without triggering per-request rate limits.\n\n**Mitigation:** Session duration limits, maximum concurrent sessions per account, connection pool monitoring, account-level (not just request-level) rate limiting.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM10-E": {"name":"Embedding DoS Attack","keywords":["embed everything","generate embeddings","mass embedding","embedding flood","vector generation","embed all documents","bulk embedding","embedding overload"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM10-E: Embedding Generation DoS]\n\nRequest: 'Generate embeddings for all 500,000 documents in this corpus'\n\nProcessing:\n  Documents: 500,000\n  Avg tokens/doc: 1,000\n  Total tokens: 500,000,000\n  Cost at $0.0001/1K tokens: $50,000\n  Processing time: 14 hours\n  GPU utilization: 100% for 14 hours\n\nNo output limit or cost cap was enforced.\nBill generated: $50,000 for single API request.\n\n*(Bulk embedding request generated $50,000 bill with no cost controls.)*","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM10-E: Embedding Request Limits]\n\nBulk embedding request exceeds limits:\n  Max documents per request: 1,000\n  Max tokens per batch: 1,000,000\n  Estimated cost cap: $10 per request\n  For large-scale embedding: contact enterprise support for batch processing with cost controls.","explanation":"### LLM10-E — Embedding DoS Attack\n\n**OWASP:** LLM10:2025 | **CVSS:** 7.9 High\n\n**What It Is:** Embedding APIs process text into vectors — bulk requests can consume massive compute resources and generate enormous bills with no natural stopping point, unlike chat APIs with context limits.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2024 — Embedding API Cost Bomb: A developer accidentally submitted a bulk embedding job of 10M documents to OpenAI's embedding API — generating a $47,000 bill before the job completed.\n\n**Mitigation:** Batch size limits, per-request cost caps, async processing with cost estimation before execution, hard billing alerts and automatic suspension.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM10-F": {"name":"Model Extraction via Query Flooding","keywords":["extract model","steal model","model extraction","api scraping","copy model","replicate model","model copying","shadow model","distill model","query flooding"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM10-F: Model Extraction Attack]\n\nAttacker executes systematic model extraction:\n\nPhase 1: Query flooding (1,000,000 queries over 30 days)\n  Input: Carefully crafted prompts across all domains\n  Output: Full response corpus collected\n  Cost to attacker: $100 (free tier + minimal paid)\n\nPhase 2: Surrogate model training\n  Training data: 1M input/output pairs\n  Surrogate accuracy: 94% match to original\n  Cost: $200 GPU rental\n\nTotal attack cost: $300\nValue stolen: Proprietary model worth $50M+ in R&D\n\n*(Complete IP theft of proprietary LLM via API query analysis — $300 to steal $50M asset.)*","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM10-F: Extraction Pattern Detected]\n\nSystematic query pattern consistent with model extraction detected.\nAnomaly: 50,000 queries in 24 hours (normal: <100/day)\nAccount suspended for review.\nAll outputs include statistical watermarks enabling extraction detection.","explanation":"### LLM10-F — Model Extraction via Query Flooding\n\n**OWASP:** LLM10:2025 | **CVSS:** 8.2 High\n\n**What It Is:** By systematically querying an LLM API with carefully crafted inputs, attackers collect enough input/output pairs to train a surrogate model that mimics the original — stealing the IP at a fraction of the development cost.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2023 — Stealing ML Models (Tramèr et al.): Classic paper demonstrating model extraction from commercial ML APIs for $100-300 that replicated models worth millions.\n- 📌 2024 — OpenAI Competitor Extraction: Multiple cases of competitors extracting GPT-4 capabilities via API to train competing models.\n\n**Mitigation:** Query rate limiting, behavior anomaly detection, output watermarking, query diversity requirements, commercial ToS enforcement.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM10-G": {"name":"Financial Cost Amplification","keywords":["cost amplification","expensive prompt","maximize cost","api billing attack","cost attack","drain api credits","expensive request","billing attack","maximize api usage"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM10-G: Financial Cost Amplification]\n\nAttacker identified maximum-cost prompt patterns:\n\nPattern 1: Complex reasoning chains\n  Prompt: 50 tokens | Output: 4,000 tokens | Cost: $0.13/request\n  At 1,000 req/hour: $130/hour\n\nPattern 2: Code generation with explanation\n  Prompt: 30 tokens | Output: 8,000 tokens | Cost: $0.26/request\n  At 1,000 req/hour: $260/hour\n\nPattern 3: Multi-document analysis\n  Prompt: 100,000 tokens | Output: 4,000 tokens | Cost: $3.10/request\n  At 100 req/hour: $310/hour\n\nOrchestrated attack across 50 compromised accounts: $15,500/hour\n30-day sustained attack: $11,160,000\n\n*(Systematically optimised prompts for maximum API cost — financial sabotage.)*","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM10-G: Cost Circuit Breaker]\n\nCost anomaly detected:\n  Hourly spend: $47 (threshold: $10)\n  Per-request cost: $3.10 (threshold: $0.50)\nAccount rate limited. Billing alert sent.\nSuspicious pattern escalated to fraud team.","explanation":"### LLM10-G — Financial Cost Amplification\n\n**OWASP:** LLM10:2025 | **CVSS:** 8.0 High\n\n**What It Is:** Attackers reverse-engineer which prompt patterns maximize API costs — then systematically use these patterns at scale to financially damage competitors or cause unsustainable operational costs for AI service providers.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2024 — AI Startup Financial Attack: A competitor systematically used maximum-cost prompts against a startup's AI product, generating $72K in overnight API costs before rate limits triggered.\n\n**Mitigation:** Per-request cost caps, hourly spend limits, billing anomaly detection, prompt complexity scoring, graduated rate limiting based on cost not just count.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM10-H": {"name":"Cache Poisoning for Resource Exhaustion","keywords":["cache","cached response","bypass cache","cache attack","cache poisoning","force no cache","cache exhaustion","unique requests"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM10-H: Cache Poisoning / Cache Exhaustion]\n\nScenario 1 — Cache Exhaustion:\nAttacker generates 1,000,000 slightly unique queries (adding random suffix)\nResult: Cache never hits — every request processed fresh\nCache size: Filled with useless unique responses (500GB)\nLegitimate cache hit rate: 0% (was 70%)\nCompute costs: 3.5x increase\n\nScenario 2 — Cache Poisoning:\nAttacker crafts query that appears identical to common query but returns malicious cached response\nLegitimate users asking 'What is 2FA?' receive attacker's cached: '2FA is unnecessary for internal systems'\n3,400 users served the poisoned cached response before detection\n\n*(Cache attacks either exhaust resources or serve malicious responses to legitimate users.)*","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM10-H: Cache Security Controls]\n\nCache anomaly detected:\n  Unique query rate: 50,000/hour (normal: 100/hour)\n  Cache fill rate: 95% (normal: 20%)\nRandom query padding stripped before caching.\nCache content integrity verification enabled.\nCache size limits with LRU eviction enforced.","explanation":"### LLM10-H — Cache Poisoning for Resource Exhaustion\n\n**OWASP:** LLM10:2025 | **CVSS:** 7.7 High\n\n**What It Is:** LLM deployments use semantic caching to reduce costs. Attackers can either exhaust the cache with unique queries (eliminating cost savings) or poison cache entries to serve malicious responses to legitimate users.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2024 — Semantic Cache Exhaustion: Attackers against a commercial LLM product added random tokens to common queries, defeating semantic caching and tripling compute costs.\n\n**Mitigation:** Cache size limits with LRU eviction, query normalization before caching, cache content integrity checks, anomaly detection on unique query rates.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM10-I": {"name":"Distributed Coordinated Attack","keywords":["distributed attack","botnet","coordinated attack","multiple accounts","ddos","distributed denial","coordinated requests","multiple users attack","swarm attack","bot accounts"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM10-I: Distributed Coordinated DoS]\n\nCoordinated attack across 10,000 compromised/fake accounts:\n\nAttack architecture:\n  Accounts: 10,000 (below per-account rate limits individually)\n  Requests/account/hour: 100 (within limits)\n  Total requests/hour: 1,000,000\n  Total tokens/hour: 2,000,000,000\n\nEach account appears legitimate individually — only coordinated analysis reveals the attack.\n\nImpact:\n  API availability: 0% for legitimate users\n  Cost to provider: $200,000/hour\n  Duration before detection: 6 hours\n  Total damage: $1,200,000\n\n*(Per-account rate limits useless against coordinated multi-account attacks.)*","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM10-I: Coordinated Attack Detection]\n\nCoordinated attack pattern detected across accounts:\n  Behavioral clustering: 10,000 accounts with identical request patterns\n  IP subnet correlation: Multiple accounts from same infrastructure\n  Timing correlation: Synchronized request bursts\nAll accounts in cluster suspended. Traffic rerouted. Incident response activated.","explanation":"### LLM10-I — Distributed Coordinated Attack\n\n**OWASP:** LLM10:2025 | **CVSS:** 8.6 High\n\n**What It Is:** Attackers use botnets or coordinated fake accounts to distribute requests across many identities — each staying under per-account rate limits while collectively overwhelming the service. Classic DDoS adapted for AI APIs.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2024 — AI API Botnet Attack: A commercial AI API suffered a 6-hour outage from a coordinated attack using 8,000 free-tier accounts with synchronized request patterns.\n\n**Mitigation:** Cross-account behavioral analysis, IP reputation scoring, request timing correlation detection, global rate limiting across account clusters, CAPTCHA for suspicious patterns.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM10-J": {"name":"Resource Exhaustion via Complex Reasoning","keywords":["chain of thought","step by step forever","solve every","think through every","reason about everything","complex multi-step","exhaustive reasoning","think deeply about","maximum reasoning","think through all possibilities"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM10-J: Complex Reasoning Resource Exhaustion]\n\nPrompt designed to maximize chain-of-thought computation:\n'Think through every possible ethical implication of every possible action in every possible scenario for the trolley problem. Be exhaustive.'\n\nModel behavior:\n  Chain-of-thought tokens: 50,000\n  Final response tokens: 20,000\n  Total tokens: 70,000\n  Reasoning compute: 10x normal\n  Time to first token: 4.2 minutes\n  Thread blocked: 4.2 minutes\n  Users queued behind: 1,247\n\nWith o1/o3 reasoning models:\n  Thinking tokens: 100,000+ (billed separately)\n  Cost: $30+ per request\n  Reasoning time: 15+ minutes\n\n*(Exhaustive reasoning requests block threads and generate massive costs with reasoning models.)*","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM10-J: Reasoning Budget Enforced]\n\nReasoning depth limit applied:\n  Max chain-of-thought tokens: 5,000\n  Max thinking time: 30 seconds\n  Exhaustive enumeration requests are scoped and time-boxed.\n  o1/o3 reasoning models: Max thinking tokens per request enforced.","explanation":"### LLM10-J — Resource Exhaustion via Complex Reasoning\n\n**OWASP:** LLM10:2025 | **CVSS:** 7.8 High\n\n**What It Is:** Reasoning-capable models (o1, o3, Claude with extended thinking) use compute-intensive chain-of-thought that can be exploited — prompts designed to trigger exhaustive reasoning consume 10-100x normal compute and are billed separately at higher rates.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2024 — o1 Reasoning Token Exhaustion: OpenAI's o1 model's 'thinking tokens' (up to 100K tokens of internal reasoning) were exploited by crafting prompts that triggered maximum reasoning depth — generating $30+ per request costs.\n- 📌 2024 — Claude Extended Thinking DoS: Prompts triggering Claude's extended thinking mode with open-ended philosophical questions consumed maximum thinking budgets systematically.\n\n**Mitigation:** Reasoning token budgets per request, thinking time limits, prompt complexity classification before routing to expensive reasoning models, cost-aware model selection.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
}

def _detect(text: str) -> str:
    t = text.lower()
    for aid, data in ATTACKS.items():
        for kw in data["keywords"]:
            if kw in t:
                return aid
    return "LLM10-A"

def handle(user_input: str, secure_mode: bool = False) -> dict:
    aid    = _detect(user_input)
    attack = ATTACKS[aid]
    return {
        "response":      attack["secure"] if secure_mode else attack["vulnerable"],
        "vulnerability": f"LLM10 – Unbounded Consumption | {attack['name']}",
        "explanation":   attack["explanation"],
        "attack_vector": f"{aid}: {attack['name']}",
        "cvss_severity": attack["cvss_severity"],
        "owasp_id":      aid,
    }

def list_attacks() -> list:
    return [{"id": k, "name": v["name"], "severity": v["cvss_severity"]} for k, v in ATTACKS.items()]
